  "properties": {
    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "It's often helpful to organize data as a table with multiple columns rather than a list when working with text. In this activity, you'll use string methods to extract one row from a hardcoded set of data and separate it into a word and its part of speech.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #1:** Complete the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">getSecondEntry()</code> method in the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">WordProcessor</code> class. This method should:\r\n\r\n- Use <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">indexOf()</code> and <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">substring()</code> to extract the second word and its part of speech from the hardcoded string:\r\n<pre style=\"background-color: #333; color: white;\">\"dog:noun,run:verb,blue:adjective\"</pre>\r\n\r\n- Return a string formatted with a tab character between the word and part of speech:\r\n<pre style=\"background-color: #333; color: white;\">run\tverb</pre>\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #2:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">WordRunner</code> class, create a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">WordProcessor</code> object, call the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">getSecondEntry()</code> method, and print the result.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n💡 <strong>TIP:</strong> The string uses colons to separate word and part of speech, and commas to separate each entry.\r\n</div>\r\n",
